---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { withBase } from '@/lib/withBase';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import BitField from '@/components/react/BitField.tsx';
import ValueTable from '@/components/ui/ValueTable.astro';
import Formula from '@/components/ui/Formula.astro';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
import DocRef from '@/components/ui/DocRef.astro';
import { MACK, TAG_INFO } from '@/data/fields';
import { ADKD_TABLE, COP_TABLE, PRN_D_TABLE } from '@/data/tables';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="MACK message"
  description="The MACK message: the tags and disclosed TESLA key that authenticate Galileo navigation data."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="3 · Data structures"
    title="The MACK message"
    lead="The fast OSNMA stream: 480 bits per subframe carrying the tags that authenticate the previous subframe's data, followed by the key that unlocks them."
  />

  <p>
    Where HKROOT trickles out the keys and signatures slowly, the
    <strong>MACK</strong> message moves fast — 32 bits per page, assembled into 480
    bits every 30 seconds <DocRef doc="icd" section="4" />. It carries two things:
    a set of <strong>tags</strong> (truncated MACs over navigation data) and the
    <strong>TESLA key</strong> that verifies the tags sent one subframe earlier.
  </p>

  <h2>The layout</h2>

  <BitField spec={MACK} client:visible />

  <p>
    The message opens with a header: <strong>Tag0</strong> (the transmitting
    satellite's own self-authentication tag), a 12-bit <strong>MACSEQ</strong>, and
    a 4-bit <strong>COP</strong>. Then come the remaining tag slots — each a tag
    plus a 16-bit Tag-Info — followed by the disclosed <strong>Key</strong> and
    zero <strong>padding</strong> up to 480 bits.
  </p>

  <h2>How many tags fit</h2>
  <p>
    The number of tags depends on the key and tag sizes; every slot after Tag0
    costs <Formula tex="l_t + 16" /> bits, and the key consumes
    <Formula tex="l_K" />:
  </p>
  <Formula tex="n_t = \left\lfloor \frac{480 - l_K}{l_t + 16} \right\rfloor" display />
  <p>With the test-vector configuration (l_K = 128, l_t = 40) that leaves room for six tags.</p>

  <h2>Tag-Info: what each tag is about</h2>
  <p>Every tag after Tag0 comes with 16 bits describing what it authenticates:</p>

  <BitField spec={TAG_INFO} client:visible />

  <ValueTable table={ADKD_TABLE} />
  <ValueTable table={PRN_D_TABLE} />
  <ValueTable table={COP_TABLE} />

  <h2>Self versus cross authentication</h2>
  <p>
    Two satellites appear in every tag. <strong>PRN_A</strong> is the satellite
    transmitting the tag; <strong>PRN_D</strong> is the satellite whose navigation
    data is being authenticated. When they differ, one satellite vouches for
    another's data — <em>cross-authentication</em>, which lets a receiver
    authenticate a satellite it can barely hear. Tag0 omits PRN_D entirely: it
    always authenticates the transmitting satellite's own data
    (<em>self-authentication</em>) <DocRef doc="icd" section="4.2.1" />.
  </p>

  <Callout type="security">
    <p>
      The key in a MACK message verifies the tags from the <em>previous</em>
      subframe, never the current one. That one-subframe delay is the whole point:
      when those tags were sent, this key was still secret
      <DocRef doc="rxg" section="5.5.4" />.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <div class="level-engineer">
    <h3>How a tag is computed</h3>
    <p>A tag is a truncated MAC over a message that binds the data to a time, a counter and the status:</p>
    <Formula tex="m = (\text{PRN}_D \,\|\, \text{PRN}_A \,\|\, GST_{SF} \,\|\, \text{CTR} \,\|\, \text{NMAS} \,\|\, \text{navdata} \,\|\, P)" display />
    <Formula tex="\text{tag} = \operatorname{trunc}(l_t,\ \operatorname{mac}(K, m))" display />
    <p>
      Tag0 uses the same construction but drops PRN_D. The sequence of ADKD types
      across the tags is fixed by the
      <a href={withBase('/structures/maclt')}>MAC look-up table</a>, and the disclosed key is
      verified against the chain on the
      <a href={withBase('/machinery/tesla-chain')}>TESLA key chain</a> page.
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
